A reusable custom hook that syncs state to localStorage while remaining SSR-safe. The key trick is initializing from localStorage inside a lazy initializer and listening for storage events across tabs.

```typescript
import { useState, useEffect, useCallback } from 'react';

function useLocalStorage<T>(key: string, initialValue: T) {
  const [storedValue, setStoredValue] = useState<T>(() => {
    if (typeof window === 'undefined') return initialValue;
    try {
      const item = window.localStorage.getItem(key);
      return item ? (JSON.parse(item) as T) : initialValue;
    } catch {
      return initialValue;
    }
  });

  const setValue = useCallback((value: T | ((prev: T) => T)) => {
    setStoredValue((prev) => {
      const nextValue = value instanceof Function ? value(prev) : value;
      window.localStorage.setItem(key, JSON.stringify(nextValue));
      return nextValue;
    });
  }, [key]);

  useEffect(() => {
    const handler = (e: StorageEvent) => {
      if (e.key === key && e.newValue) {
        setStoredValue(JSON.parse(e.newValue));
      }
    };
    window.addEventListener('storage', handler);
    return () => window.removeEventListener('storage', handler);
  }, [key]);

  return [storedValue, setValue] as const;
}
```

The storage event listener ensures multiple tabs stay in sync. Always wrap `JSON.parse` in try/catch since localStorage may contain invalid data from older app versions.

`useDebugValue` labels custom hooks in React DevTools, making it easier to inspect hook state. It accepts an optional formatter function that runs only when DevTools is open, avoiding perf costs.

```typescript
import { useDebugValue, useSyncExternalStore } from 'react';

function useOnlineStatus() {
  const isOnline = useSyncExternalStore(
    (callback) => {
      window.addEventListener('online', callback);
      window.addEventListener('offline', callback);
      return () => {
        window.removeEventListener('online', callback);
        window.removeEventListener('offline', callback);
      };
    },
    () => navigator.onLine,
    () => true // server snapshot
  );

  // Simple label
  useDebugValue(isOnline ? 'Online' : 'Offline');

  return isOnline;
}

// With expensive formatting — formatter only runs when DevTools inspects
function useQuery<T>(key: string) {
  const data = useCacheSubscription<T>(key);
  useDebugValue(data, (d) =>
    `${key}: ${d ? `${JSON.stringify(d).slice(0, 50)}...` : 'loading'}`
  );
  return data;
}
```

Only use `useDebugValue` in shared/library hooks. For app-level hooks, React DevTools already displays the inner hook state, making the label redundant.

`useSyncExternalStore` is the correct way to subscribe React components to external data sources (browser APIs, third-party stores, vanilla JS modules). It prevents tearing during concurrent rendering.

```typescript
import { useSyncExternalStore } from 'react';

// Example: subscribe to window width
function useWindowWidth() {
  return useSyncExternalStore(
    (callback) => {
      window.addEventListener('resize', callback);
      return () => window.removeEventListener('resize', callback);
    },
    () => window.innerWidth,    // client snapshot
    () => 1024                  // server snapshot (SSR fallback)
  );
}

// Example: Zustand-like external store
function createStore<T>(initial: T) {
  let state = initial;
  const listeners = new Set<() => void>();
  return {
    getSnapshot: () => state,
    subscribe: (cb: () => void) => {
      listeners.add(cb);
      return () => listeners.delete(cb);
    },
    setState: (fn: (prev: T) => T) => {
      state = fn(state);
      listeners.forEach((cb) => cb());
    },
  };
}

const counterStore = createStore({ count: 0 });

function Counter() {
  const { count } = useSyncExternalStore(
    counterStore.subscribe,
    counterStore.getSnapshot
  );
  return <p>{count}</p>;
}
```

Always provide a `getServerSnapshot` (3rd arg) when the store is unavailable during SSR. The snapshot must return an immutable value — return a new object reference only when data actually changes.

`useId` generates stable, unique IDs that are consistent between server and client rendering, solving hydration mismatch issues with manual ID generation.

```tsx
import { useId } from 'react';

function FormField({ label, type = 'text' }: { label: string; type?: string }) {
  const id = useId();
  return (
    <div>
      <label htmlFor={id}>{label}</label>
      <input id={id} type={type} />
    </div>
  );
}

// Multiple related IDs from one useId call
function PasswordField() {
  const id = useId();
  return (
    <div>
      <label htmlFor={`${id}-input`}>Password</label>
      <input id={`${id}-input`} type="password" aria-describedby={`${id}-hint`} />
      <p id={`${id}-hint`}>Must be at least 8 characters</p>
    </div>
  );
}

// With identifierPrefix for micro-frontends
// In createRoot or hydrateRoot:
createRoot(document.getElementById('app')!, {
  identifierPrefix: 'app1-',
});
```

Do NOT use `useId` for list keys — it generates the same ID on every render of that component instance. Use data-driven keys for lists. The `:r1:` format of generated IDs is intentional — colons are valid in HTML IDs and unlikely to collide with user-defined IDs.

Compound components share implicit state through context, giving consumers a flexible, declarative API similar to `<select>` + `<option>`. Parent manages state; children read it.

```tsx
import { createContext, useContext, useState, ReactNode } from 'react';

type AccordionCtx = {
  openIndex: number | null;
  toggle: (i: number) => void;
};
const AccordionContext = createContext<AccordionCtx | null>(null);

function useAccordion() {
  const ctx = useContext(AccordionContext);
  if (!ctx) throw new Error('Accordion.* must be used within <Accordion>');
  return ctx;
}

function Accordion({ children }: { children: ReactNode }) {
  const [openIndex, setOpenIndex] = useState<number | null>(null);
  const toggle = (i: number) => setOpenIndex((prev) => (prev === i ? null : i));
  return (
    <AccordionContext.Provider value={{ openIndex, toggle }}>
      <div role="region">{children}</div>
    </AccordionContext.Provider>
  );
}

function Item({ index, title, children }: { index: number; title: string; children: ReactNode }) {
  const { openIndex, toggle } = useAccordion();
  return (
    <div>
      <button onClick={() => toggle(index)}>{title}</button>
      {openIndex === index && <div>{children}</div>}
    </div>
  );
}

Accordion.Item = Item;

// Usage:
// <Accordion>
//   <Accordion.Item index={0} title="FAQ 1">Answer 1</Accordion.Item>
//   <Accordion.Item index={1} title="FAQ 2">Answer 2</Accordion.Item>
// </Accordion>
```

This pattern is used by Radix UI, Headless UI, and Reach UI. Attach sub-components as static properties on the parent for clean dot-notation imports.

Render props delegate rendering control to the consumer via a function prop. While hooks have largely replaced this pattern, it remains useful for components that own DOM behavior (mouse tracking, intersection observers).

```tsx
import { useState, useEffect, useRef, ReactNode } from 'react';

type IntersectionRenderProps = {
  children: (args: { isVisible: boolean; ref: React.RefObject<HTMLDivElement> }) => ReactNode;
  threshold?: number;
};

function IntersectionObserverComponent({ children, threshold = 0.5 }: IntersectionRenderProps) {
  const ref = useRef<HTMLDivElement>(null!);
  const [isVisible, setIsVisible] = useState(false);

  useEffect(() => {
    const observer = new IntersectionObserver(
      ([entry]) => setIsVisible(entry.isIntersecting),
      { threshold }
    );
    if (ref.current) observer.observe(ref.current);
    return () => observer.disconnect();
  }, [threshold]);

  return <>{children({ isVisible, ref })}</>;
}

// Usage
function LazySection() {
  return (
    <IntersectionObserverComponent threshold={0.3}>
      {({ isVisible, ref }) => (
        <div ref={ref}>
          {isVisible ? <HeavyChart /> : <Placeholder />}
        </div>
      )}
    </IntersectionObserverComponent>
  );
}
```

Prefer hooks for simple state/effect sharing. Use render props when the component must own a ref or coordinate multiple DOM elements, or when building a headless library that supports both React and Preact.

HOCs wrap a component to inject props. They are less common since hooks, but still useful for cross-cutting concerns in class components or when you need to wrap many components identically (e.g., auth guards, analytics).

```tsx
import { ComponentType, useEffect } from 'react';

type WithAuthProps = { userId: string; role: string };

function withAuth<P extends object>(WrappedComponent: ComponentType<P & WithAuthProps>) {
  function AuthenticatedComponent(props: Omit<P, keyof WithAuthProps>) {
    const { userId, role } = useSession(); // your auth hook

    if (!userId) return <Navigate to="/login" />;

    return <WrappedComponent {...(props as P)} userId={userId} role={role} />;
  }

  AuthenticatedComponent.displayName =
    `withAuth(${WrappedComponent.displayName || WrappedComponent.name || 'Component'})`;

  return AuthenticatedComponent;
}

// Usage
function Dashboard({ userId, role, title }: WithAuthProps & { title: string }) {
  return <h1>{title} — {role}</h1>;
}

const ProtectedDashboard = withAuth(Dashboard);
// <ProtectedDashboard title="Admin" /> — userId and role injected
```

Always set `displayName` on the wrapper for DevTools debugging. The `Omit<P, keyof WithAuthProps>` type ensures consumers do not pass the injected props manually. Avoid stacking many HOCs — it creates wrapper hell and makes debugging painful.

Error boundaries catch rendering errors in their subtree and display a fallback. They must be class components (no hook equivalent). Use `react-error-boundary` for a production-ready solution or write a minimal one.

```tsx
import { Component, ErrorInfo, ReactNode } from 'react';

type Props = {
  children: ReactNode;
  fallback: (props: { error: Error; reset: () => void }) => ReactNode;
};

type State = { error: Error | null };

class ErrorBoundary extends Component<Props, State> {
  state: State = { error: null };

  static getDerivedStateFromError(error: Error): State {
    return { error };
  }

  componentDidCatch(error: Error, info: ErrorInfo) {
    console.error('ErrorBoundary caught:', error, info.componentStack);
    // Send to Sentry, DataDog, etc.
  }

  reset = () => this.setState({ error: null });

  render() {
    if (this.state.error) {
      return this.props.fallback({ error: this.state.error, reset: this.reset });
    }
    return this.props.children;
  }
}

// Usage
<ErrorBoundary
  fallback={({ error, reset }) => (
    <div role="alert">
      <p>Something went wrong: {error.message}</p>
      <button onClick={reset}>Try again</button>
    </div>
  )}
>
  <RiskyFeature />
</ErrorBoundary>
```

Error boundaries do NOT catch errors in event handlers, async code, or SSR. For those, use try/catch. Place boundaries around feature sections, not the entire app, so one crash does not blank the full page.

`createPortal` renders children into a different DOM node while preserving the React tree context (events bubble through the React tree, not the DOM tree).

```tsx
import { createPortal } from 'react-dom';
import { useState, useEffect, useRef } from 'react';

function Modal({ isOpen, onClose, children }: {
  isOpen: boolean;
  onClose: () => void;
  children: React.ReactNode;
}) {
  const elRef = useRef<HTMLDivElement | null>(null);

  if (!elRef.current) {
    elRef.current = document.createElement('div');
  }

  useEffect(() => {
    const el = elRef.current!;
    document.body.appendChild(el);
    return () => { document.body.removeChild(el); };
  }, []);

  if (!isOpen) return null;

  return createPortal(
    <div className="modal-overlay" onClick={onClose}>
      <div className="modal-content" onClick={(e) => e.stopPropagation()}>
        {children}
        <button onClick={onClose}>Close</button>
      </div>
    </div>,
    elRef.current
  );
}

// Usage — context providers above <Modal> still work inside it
<ThemeProvider>
  <Modal isOpen={show} onClose={() => setShow(false)}>
    <ThemedContent /> {/* can useContext(ThemeContext) */}
  </Modal>
</ThemeProvider>
```

Portals are essential for modals, tooltips, dropdowns, and toasts that must visually escape `overflow: hidden` or `z-index` stacking contexts. Events still bubble through React's virtual tree, so parent `onClick` handlers fire as expected.

Next.js middleware runs at the edge before every matched request. It is ideal for auth checks, redirects, A/B testing, and geolocation-based routing.

```typescript
// middleware.ts (project root)
import { NextResponse } from 'next/server';
import type { NextRequest } from 'next/server';

export function middleware(request: NextRequest) {
  const token = request.cookies.get('session-token')?.value;

  // Redirect unauthenticated users
  if (!token) {
    const loginUrl = new URL('/login', request.url);
    loginUrl.searchParams.set('callbackUrl', request.nextUrl.pathname);
    return NextResponse.redirect(loginUrl);
  }

  // Add custom headers for downstream use
  const response = NextResponse.next();
  response.headers.set('x-user-authenticated', 'true');
  return response;
}

// Only run on these paths — skip static files, API routes, etc.
export const config = {
  matcher: [
    '/dashboard/:path*',
    '/settings/:path*',
    '/api/protected/:path*',
    // Negative lookahead to skip Next.js internals and static assets
    '/((?!_next/static|_next/image|favicon.ico|public/).*)',
  ],
};
```

Middleware runs in the Edge Runtime — no Node.js APIs like `fs` or `crypto.createHash`. Use the Web Crypto API instead. Keep middleware lightweight; it executes on every matched request. Avoid database calls here — verify JWTs or check cookies instead.

A common gotcha with Next.js middleware is that `matcher` patterns silently fail if written incorrectly. Trailing slashes, missing colons for dynamic segments, and incorrect negative lookaheads cause the middleware to not run at all — with no error or warning.

```typescript
// WRONG — trailing slash prevents matching
export const config = {
  matcher: ['/dashboard/'],  // Does NOT match /dashboard
};

// WRONG — missing colon for path wildcard
export const config = {
  matcher: ['/dashboard/path*'],  // Literal string 'path*'
};

// CORRECT
export const config = {
  matcher: [
    '/dashboard',           // exact match
    '/dashboard/:path*',    // /dashboard and all sub-paths
  ],
};

// WRONG — regex in matcher array (not supported)
export const config = {
  matcher: [/^\/dashboard/],
};

// CORRECT — regex-like patterns use string syntax
export const config = {
  matcher: ['/((?!api|_next/static|favicon.ico).*)'],
};
```

To debug, add a `console.log` at the top of your middleware function and check the terminal — if it never fires, the matcher is wrong. The matcher array only accepts string patterns, not RegExp objects. Each string is compiled to a path-to-regexp pattern internally.

Middleware supports three response types: `redirect` (HTTP 3xx), `rewrite` (internal proxy), and `next()` (continue with optional header modifications).

```typescript
import { NextResponse } from 'next/server';
import type { NextRequest } from 'next/server';

export function middleware(request: NextRequest) {
  const { pathname, searchParams } = request.nextUrl;
  const country = request.geo?.country ?? 'US';

  // 1. Permanent redirect (301)
  if (pathname === '/old-page') {
    return NextResponse.redirect(new URL('/new-page', request.url), 301);
  }

  // 2. Rewrite — serve different content at same URL (A/B test)
  if (pathname === '/pricing') {
    const bucket = request.cookies.get('ab-bucket')?.value ?? 'control';
    return NextResponse.rewrite(
      new URL(`/pricing/${bucket}`, request.url)
    );
  }

  // 3. Geo-based rewrite
  if (pathname === '/' && country === 'DE') {
    return NextResponse.rewrite(new URL('/de', request.url));
  }

  // 4. Set response cookie and continue
  const response = NextResponse.next();
  if (!request.cookies.has('visitor-id')) {
    response.cookies.set('visitor-id', crypto.randomUUID(), {
      httpOnly: true,
      maxAge: 60 * 60 * 24 * 365,
    });
  }
  return response;
}
```

Rewrites are invisible to the user — the URL bar stays the same. Redirects change the URL. Use rewrites for A/B tests and locale routing; use redirects for permanent URL changes and auth flows.

The `next/image` component automatically optimizes images with lazy loading, responsive sizing, and modern formats (WebP/AVIF). It prevents Cumulative Layout Shift (CLS) by requiring dimensions.

```tsx
import Image from 'next/image';

// Static import — dimensions inferred at build time
import heroImg from '@/public/hero.jpg';

export default function Hero() {
  return (
    <Image
      src={heroImg}
      alt="Hero banner"
      placeholder="blur"       // auto blur placeholder from static import
      priority                  // preload above-the-fold images
      sizes="(max-width: 768px) 100vw, 50vw"
    />
  );
}

// Remote images — must configure domains in next.config
export function Avatar({ url }: { url: string }) {
  return (
    <Image
      src={url}
      alt="User avatar"
      width={48}
      height={48}
      className="rounded-full"
    />
  );
}

// next.config.js
module.exports = {
  images: {
    remotePatterns: [
      { protocol: 'https', hostname: '**.cloudinary.com' },
      { protocol: 'https', hostname: 'avatars.githubusercontent.com' },
    ],
    formats: ['image/avif', 'image/webp'],
  },
};
```

Always set `priority` on the Largest Contentful Paint (LCP) image — typically the hero banner. Use `sizes` to help the browser pick the correct responsive image. For `fill` mode, the parent element must have `position: relative`.

`next/font` downloads fonts at build time and self-hosts them, eliminating layout shift and external network requests. It supports both Google Fonts and local font files.

```tsx
// app/layout.tsx
import { Inter, JetBrains_Mono } from 'next/font/google';
import localFont from 'next/font/local';

const inter = Inter({
  subsets: ['latin'],
  display: 'swap',
  variable: '--font-inter',
});

const jetbrains = JetBrains_Mono({
  subsets: ['latin'],
  variable: '--font-mono',
});

// Local font
const calSans = localFont({
  src: '../public/fonts/CalSans-SemiBold.woff2',
  variable: '--font-calsans',
  display: 'swap',
});

export default function RootLayout({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  return (
    <html lang="en" className={`${inter.variable} ${jetbrains.variable} ${calSans.variable}`}>
      <body className={inter.className}>{children}</body>
    </html>
  );
}

// In tailwind.config.ts
module.exports = {
  theme: {
    extend: {
      fontFamily: {
        sans: ['var(--font-inter)'],
        mono: ['var(--font-mono)'],
        display: ['var(--font-calsans)'],
      },
    },
  },
};
```

Use CSS variables (`variable` option) to integrate with Tailwind. `display: 'swap'` shows fallback text immediately. For variable fonts, set `axes` to include italic or weight ranges.

The App Router metadata API replaces `next/head`. Export a `metadata` object or `generateMetadata` function from any `page.tsx` or `layout.tsx`. Metadata merges and child pages can override parent values.

```tsx
// app/layout.tsx — static metadata
import type { Metadata } from 'next';

export const metadata: Metadata = {
  metadataBase: new URL('https://example.com'),
  title: { default: 'My App', template: '%s | My App' },
  description: 'A modern web application',
  openGraph: {
    type: 'website',
    locale: 'en_US',
    siteName: 'My App',
  },
};

// app/blog/[slug]/page.tsx — dynamic metadata
import type { Metadata } from 'next';

type Props = { params: Promise<{ slug: string }> };

export async function generateMetadata({ params }: Props): Promise<Metadata> {
  const { slug } = await params;
  const post = await getPost(slug);
  return {
    title: post.title,  // becomes "Post Title | My App" via template
    description: post.excerpt,
    openGraph: {
      images: [{ url: post.coverImage, width: 1200, height: 630 }],
    },
  };
}

export default async function BlogPost({ params }: Props) {
  const { slug } = await params;
  const post = await getPost(slug);
  return <article>{post.content}</article>;
}
```

The `title.template` in layouts lets you define a consistent pattern like `%s | My App`. `generateMetadata` runs in parallel with the page component, and Next.js deduplicates the fetch if both call the same endpoint.

Create `app/sitemap.ts` to generate a sitemap dynamically. Next.js automatically serves it at `/sitemap.xml`. For large sites, use `generateSitemaps` to split into multiple files.

```typescript
// app/sitemap.ts
import type { MetadataRoute } from 'next';

export default async function sitemap(): Promise<MetadataRoute.Sitemap> {
  const baseUrl = 'https://example.com';

  // Fetch all dynamic routes
  const posts = await db.post.findMany({
    select: { slug: true, updatedAt: true },
  });

  const postEntries = posts.map((post) => ({
    url: `${baseUrl}/blog/${post.slug}`,
    lastModified: post.updatedAt,
    changeFrequency: 'weekly' as const,
    priority: 0.7,
  }));

  const staticRoutes = ['', '/about', '/pricing', '/blog'].map((route) => ({
    url: `${baseUrl}${route}`,
    lastModified: new Date(),
    changeFrequency: 'monthly' as const,
    priority: route === '' ? 1.0 : 0.8,
  }));

  return [...staticRoutes, ...postEntries];
}

// For large sites (>50k URLs), split into multiple sitemaps
// app/sitemap.ts
export async function generateSitemaps() {
  const count = await db.post.count();
  const pages = Math.ceil(count / 50000);
  return Array.from({ length: pages }, (_, i) => ({ id: i }));
}

export default async function sitemap({ id }: { id: number }) {
  const posts = await db.post.findMany({
    skip: id * 50000, take: 50000,
  });
  return posts.map((post) => ({ url: `https://example.com/blog/${post.slug}` }));
}
```

Also create `app/robots.ts` to pair with the sitemap for complete SEO coverage.

Vitest + React Testing Library is the modern replacement for Jest in Vite/Next.js projects. Vitest is faster and shares config with Vite.

```typescript
// vitest.config.ts
import { defineConfig } from 'vitest/config';
import react from '@vitejs/plugin-react';

export default defineConfig({
  plugins: [react()],
  test: {
    environment: 'jsdom',
    globals: true,
    setupFiles: ['./test/setup.ts'],
    css: true,
  },
});

// test/setup.ts
import '@testing-library/jest-dom/vitest';

// components/Counter.test.tsx
import { render, screen } from '@testing-library/react';
import userEvent from '@testing-library/user-event';
import { Counter } from './Counter';

describe('Counter', () => {
  it('increments count on click', async () => {
    const user = userEvent.setup();
    render(<Counter initialCount={0} />);

    expect(screen.getByRole('heading')).toHaveTextContent('Count: 0');

    await user.click(screen.getByRole('button', { name: /increment/i }));

    expect(screen.getByRole('heading')).toHaveTextContent('Count: 1');
  });

  it('calls onChange when count changes', async () => {
    const user = userEvent.setup();
    const onChange = vi.fn();
    render(<Counter initialCount={0} onChange={onChange} />);

    await user.click(screen.getByRole('button', { name: /increment/i }));

    expect(onChange).toHaveBeenCalledWith(1);
  });
});
```

Always use `userEvent` over `fireEvent` — it simulates real browser behavior (focus, keyboard, pointer events). Query by accessible roles (`getByRole`) instead of test IDs when possible.

MSW intercepts network requests at the service worker/Node level, letting tests use real fetch calls without changing production code. Works with Vitest, Jest, Playwright, and Storybook.

```typescript
// test/mocks/handlers.ts
import { http, HttpResponse } from 'msw';

export const handlers = [
  http.get('/api/user/:id', ({ params }) => {
    return HttpResponse.json({
      id: params.id,
      name: 'Test User',
      email: 'test@example.com',
    });
  }),

  http.post('/api/login', async ({ request }) => {
    const body = await request.json() as { email: string };
    if (body.email === 'bad@test.com') {
      return HttpResponse.json({ error: 'Invalid credentials' }, { status: 401 });
    }
    return HttpResponse.json({ token: 'mock-jwt-token' });
  }),
];

// test/mocks/server.ts
import { setupServer } from 'msw/node';
import { handlers } from './handlers';
export const server = setupServer(...handlers);

// test/setup.ts
import { server } from './mocks/server';
beforeAll(() => server.listen({ onUnhandledRequest: 'error' }));
afterEach(() => server.resetHandlers());
afterAll(() => server.close());

// UserProfile.test.tsx
import { server } from '../mocks/server';
import { http, HttpResponse } from 'msw';

it('shows error on failed fetch', async () => {
  server.use(
    http.get('/api/user/:id', () => HttpResponse.json(null, { status: 500 }))
  );
  render(<UserProfile id="1" />);
  expect(await screen.findByText(/error/i)).toBeInTheDocument();
});
```

Use `server.use()` for per-test overrides — they auto-reset after each test via `server.resetHandlers()`. Set `onUnhandledRequest: 'error'` to catch missing handlers early.

When testing components that render asynchronously (data fetching, lazy loading), use `findBy*` queries which return Promises and retry until found or timeout.

```tsx
import { render, screen, within, waitForElementToBeRemoved } from '@testing-library/react';
import userEvent from '@testing-library/user-event';
import { UserList } from './UserList';

it('loads and displays users', async () => {
  render(<UserList />);

  // Wait for loading state to disappear
  expect(screen.getByText(/loading/i)).toBeInTheDocument();
  await waitForElementToBeRemoved(() => screen.queryByText(/loading/i));

  // findBy retries until element appears (default 1s timeout)
  const list = await screen.findByRole('list');
  const items = within(list).getAllByRole('listitem');
  expect(items).toHaveLength(3);
});

it('filters users by search input', async () => {
  const user = userEvent.setup();
  render(<UserList />);

  // Wait for data to load
  await screen.findByRole('list');

  // Type in search box
  await user.type(screen.getByPlaceholderText(/search/i), 'alice');

  // Wait for filtered results
  await waitForElementToBeRemoved(() => screen.queryByText('Bob'));
  expect(screen.getByText('Alice')).toBeInTheDocument();
  expect(screen.queryByText('Bob')).not.toBeInTheDocument();
});
```

Never use `waitFor` with `getBy` — it throws immediately. Use `queryBy` to assert absence (`queryByText` returns null instead of throwing) and `findBy` to wait for presence. Increase the timeout for slow CI: `findByText('...', {}, { timeout: 3000 })`.

A single context with both state and dispatch causes all consumers to re-render on every state change — even components that only call dispatch. Split them into two contexts to fix this.

```tsx
import { createContext, useContext, useReducer, ReactNode } from 'react';

type State = { count: number; name: string };
type Action = { type: 'increment' } | { type: 'setName'; payload: string };

const StateContext = createContext<State | null>(null);
const DispatchContext = createContext<React.Dispatch<Action> | null>(null);

function reducer(state: State, action: Action): State {
  switch (action.type) {
    case 'increment': return { ...state, count: state.count + 1 };
    case 'setName': return { ...state, name: action.payload };
  }
}

function AppProvider({ children }: { children: ReactNode }) {
  const [state, dispatch] = useReducer(reducer, { count: 0, name: '' });
  return (
    <DispatchContext.Provider value={dispatch}>
      <StateContext.Provider value={state}>
        {children}
      </StateContext.Provider>
    </DispatchContext.Provider>
  );
}

// This component only dispatches — it never re-renders on state change
function IncrementButton() {
  const dispatch = useContext(DispatchContext)!;
  console.log('IncrementButton render'); // only renders once
  return <button onClick={() => dispatch({ type: 'increment' })}>+1</button>;
}

// This component reads state — it re-renders on change
function CountDisplay() {
  const { count } = useContext(StateContext)!;
  return <span>{count}</span>;
}
```

Dispatch is a stable reference from `useReducer`, so the DispatchContext provider value never changes. This pattern eliminates unnecessary re-renders for action-only consumers like buttons and forms.

When a context provider re-renders, ALL consumers re-render — even if the value has not changed. This happens because object literals create new references on every render.

```tsx
import { createContext, useState, useMemo, ReactNode } from 'react';

// BAD — creates new object every render, all consumers re-render
function AppProvider({ children }: { children: ReactNode }) {
  const [user, setUser] = useState({ name: 'Alice' });
  const [theme, setTheme] = useState('dark');

  return (
    <AppContext.Provider value={{ user, theme, setUser, setTheme }}>
      {children}
    </AppContext.Provider>
  );
}

// GOOD — memoize the value object
function AppProvider({ children }: { children: ReactNode }) {
  const [user, setUser] = useState({ name: 'Alice' });
  const [theme, setTheme] = useState('dark');

  const value = useMemo(
    () => ({ user, theme, setUser, setTheme }),
    [user, theme]
  );

  return (
    <AppContext.Provider value={value}>
      {children}
    </AppContext.Provider>
  );
}
```

Even with `useMemo`, consumers that select `user` will re-render when `theme` changes because they subscribe to the whole context object. For fine-grained subscriptions, either split into multiple contexts (`UserContext`, `ThemeContext`) or use a state library like Zustand or Jotai which support selectors.

Incremental Static Regeneration (ISR) lets you update static pages after build. Use time-based revalidation or on-demand revalidation via `revalidateTag` / `revalidatePath` for instant cache invalidation.

```tsx
// app/blog/[slug]/page.tsx
export const revalidate = 3600; // revalidate every hour (time-based)

export default async function BlogPost({ params }: { params: Promise<{ slug: string }> }) {
  const { slug } = await params;
  const post = await fetch(`https://api.example.com/posts/${slug}`, {
    next: { tags: [`post-${slug}`, 'posts'] },  // tag for on-demand
  }).then((r) => r.json());
  return <article>{post.content}</article>;
}

// app/api/revalidate/route.ts — webhook handler
import { revalidateTag } from 'next/cache';
import { NextRequest, NextResponse } from 'next/server';

export async function POST(request: NextRequest) {
  const secret = request.headers.get('x-revalidate-secret');
  if (secret !== process.env.REVALIDATE_SECRET) {
    return NextResponse.json({ error: 'Invalid secret' }, { status: 401 });
  }

  const { tag } = await request.json();
  revalidateTag(tag);  // invalidate all fetches with this tag
  return NextResponse.json({ revalidated: true, tag });
}

// From your CMS webhook, call:
// POST /api/revalidate { "tag": "post-my-slug" }
// This instantly purges the cached page
```

`revalidateTag` invalidates all `fetch` calls tagged with that string. `revalidatePath('/blog/my-slug')` invalidates a specific path. On-demand revalidation is preferred over short time-based intervals for content that changes unpredictably.

Setting `output: 'export'` in `next.config.js` generates a fully static site (HTML/CSS/JS) that can be deployed to any static hosting provider (S3, Cloudflare Pages, GitHub Pages).

```javascript
// next.config.js
module.exports = {
  output: 'export',
  // Optional: set a base path for subdirectory hosting
  // basePath: '/my-app',
  images: {
    unoptimized: true, // next/image optimization requires a server
  },
};
```

**What works:** Static pages, client-side rendering, `generateStaticParams`, `useSearchParams`, dynamic routes with `generateStaticParams`.

**What does NOT work with static export:**
- Server-side rendering (no `getServerSideProps` / server components with dynamic data)
- API routes (`app/api/` or `pages/api/`)
- Middleware
- ISR / `revalidate`
- `next/image` optimization (use `unoptimized: true`)
- `headers()`, `cookies()`, `redirect()` in server components

```tsx
// Dynamic routes need generateStaticParams
// app/blog/[slug]/page.tsx
export async function generateStaticParams() {
  const posts = await getAllPosts();
  return posts.map((post) => ({ slug: post.slug }));
}
```

Static export is ideal for documentation sites, marketing pages, and dashboards that fetch data client-side. For anything needing server logic, use `output: 'standalone'` instead.

Runtime CSS-in-JS libraries like styled-components and Emotion inject styles via JavaScript at render time. This fundamentally conflicts with React Server Components (RSC), which execute on the server and cannot run client-side JavaScript.

```tsx
// This FAILS in a Server Component:
import styled from 'styled-components';

const Title = styled.h1`color: red;`; // Error: createContext is not available in RSC

export default function Page() {
  return <Title>Hello</Title>;
}

// Error message:
// "createContext only works in Client Components. Add the 'use client' directive"
```

**Workarounds:**

1. Mark every styled component file with `'use client'`:
```tsx
'use client';
import styled from 'styled-components';
export const Title = styled.h1`color: red;`;
```

2. Use `styled-components` with Next.js SSR registry:
```tsx
// app/lib/StyledRegistry.tsx
'use client';
import { useState } from 'react';
import { useServerInsertedHTML } from 'next/navigation';
import { ServerStyleSheet, StyleSheetManager } from 'styled-components';

export default function StyledRegistry({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  const [sheet] = useState(() => new ServerStyleSheet());
  useServerInsertedHTML(() => {
    const styles = sheet.getStyleElement();
    sheet.instance.clearTag();
    return <>{styles}</>;
  });
  return <StyleSheetManager sheet={sheet.instance}>{children}</StyleSheetManager>;
}
```

3. **Recommended:** Migrate to CSS Modules, Tailwind, or vanilla-extract which work natively with RSC and require zero runtime JavaScript.

Tailwind CSS works seamlessly with RSC because it generates static CSS at build time — no runtime JavaScript needed.

